? Lastly, I have greatly benefitted through this fruitful short internship on top of landing a KTP grant.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2013</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>0126BA08-B73B-48C2-A65D-BFF152D33B8A</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal,Economic</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>545ce71be499e7.26913188</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>Our experiments indicate that European sea bass (a species of marine fish) are negatively impacted by playback of pile driving noise. These results and results from a literature study were used as parameters in a model to predict the influence of underwater piling noise. The model shows that it will be a helpful tool to predict behaviour of fish to an acoustic stressor. This will be especially helpful for environmental impact assessments (EIA), during the building and operation of offshore renewable energy sites.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>? Validating the model in the field, which will further showcase the use of the model.

? Using the model for different environmental stressors (e.g. oil spillings, etc.). 

? Using the model and experimental set-ups to help predicting the impact of noise on other fish and invertebrates species.

. The outcomes of the internship have been presented on a poster at the IEC conference in Newcastle: http://www.nerc.ac.uk/innovation/activities/infrastructure/offshore/mofing-poster/

